  • Typical patient is a male older than 70, current or previous smoker.
  • 90% express TTF-1 which ?can be used for identification.
  • Hypercalcemia
    • Squamous cell CA is the commonest subtype causing this.
    • Mnemonic: (SQ-Ca --> ⬆Ca)
  • SIADH
    • euvolemic, hypoosmolar hyponatremia.
    • Lung cancer causes ectopic ADH secretion. (i.e not excessive secretion from pituitary!)
    • Management: similar to normal hyponatremia in SIADH; Free water restriction, Demeclocycline - decreases renal response to ADH, ADH receptor antagonists (conivaptan, tolvaptan).
  • Ectopic Cushing's syndrome
    + Mnemonic: Small cells will produced a fat man.
    • elevated ACTH seen in upto 50% of lung cancer patients.
    • Caused by production of ACTH from tumour cells. ACTH -> increased glucocorticoids -> hypokalemic, metabolic alkalosis.
  • Ectopic growth hormone
    • Secreted from bronchial carcinoids and epidermoid carcinomas.
  • Pulmonary carcinoid syndrome
    • Produced by bronchopulmonary neuroendocrine tumours (BP-NET) - not a rare thing.
    • Comprise about 20% of all lung cancers.
  • Lung cancer is the most common cancer associated with neurologic syndromes.
  1. Lambert Eaton syndrome ^cd77f6
    1. Paraneoplastic LEMS is invariably associated with small cell lung cancer.
    2. Autoantibodies bind to Voltage gated calcium channels on the presynaptic membrane and prevent Acetyl-choline release.
    3. Presents as proximal muscle weakness predominanly affecting the hip girdle and lower limbs. (mnemonci: lambers -> limb girdle)
    4. Diagnosis: By anti-P/Q-type voltage-gated calcium channel (VGCC) antibody testing and high frequency RNS (repetitive nerves stimulation)
    5. Targeted therapy for symptomatic LEMS with 3,4-diaminopyridine is usually first line. (aka amifampridine - it blocks calcium dependent potassium channels and prolongs the action potential, promoting release of acetylcholine).
  2. Cerebellar ataxia
  3. Sensory neuropathy
  4. Limbic encephalitis([[General medicine 6-Neurology#Q7 Autoimmune encephalitis|Autoimmune encephalitis]] - considered a classic paraneoplastic syndrome. [[LimbicSystemAndHippocampusBasalGanglia.png]]
    1. Inflammation of the limbic system (hippocampus, amygdala, hypothalamus, cingulate gyrus, limbic cortex) causes subacute (days to months) progression of neuropsychiatric symptoms - mood, memory, cognitive function and seizures. EEG and MRI support diagnosis. Can improve with immunotherapy.
    2. Most commonly associated with small cell lung cancer. Anti-Hu positive. (and Anti Ma2)
      1. Mnemonic: "Hu*** Mata Pissu"
    3. PLE usually precedes the tumour!
  • Hypercoagulability
  • Trousseau syndrome - migratory thrombophlebitis occuring in association with malignancy.
  • Nephrotic syndrome - commonest cause is [[Nephrology miscellaneous#Membranous glomerulonephritis|Membranous nephropathy]]
  • HPO - hypertrophic pulmonary osteoarthropathy (clubbing of fingers and toes)
  • Inflammatory myopathies - [[2021 General Medicine July#Polymyositis and dermatomyositis|DM and PM]]
  • Acanthosis nigricans!

Usually arises at the junction of the PCOM and the internal carotid (as shown above).

[!INFO] Management of PCOM aneurysm
Coiling - the coil promotes thrombus formation within the aneurysm which then blocks off the aneurysm.
Clipping is an invasive alternative for anterior circulation aneurysms that is technically more difficult and has higher rate of complications.

Loss of colour vision > loss of acuity = specific to optic nerve pathology

  • A delta fibers sharp - immediate pain..
  • C fibers - diffuse, dull pain.
  • Afferent pain fibers send impulses are mediated by glutamate and substance P.
  • Pain stimuli are transmitted to the thalamus and limbic system via the spinothalamic (for precise localization of pain) and the spinoreticular tract (for emotional association of pain).
  • However, the transmission of pain impulses is modulated by monoaminergic descending pathways.
    • This phenomenon is used in TENS treatment of pain.
      Sensitization: when damaged tissue becomes hypersensitive and normal stimuli become painful. This is a protective mechanism. Also called allodynia.
  • Opioid receptors: Stimulated by endorphins or opioids. They inhibit pain. Found in the spinal cord and PAG (peri aqueductal gray matter).
    • 3 Types of opioid receptors: μ-mu, δ-delta and κ-kappa distributed widely through the CNS. Opioid receptors are G-protein coupled receptors. Source
      • μ-mu -endorphins (morphine is a u-receptor agonist)
        • Enkephalins act to attenuate substance P release in the dorsal horn. Source
  • Noradrenaline and 5-HT (Serotonin) are found in descending inhibitory pathways.Source
  • Vanilloid receptor is activated by capsaicin (producing pain).

neuropathic pain

  • causes of neuropathic pain include
    • post herpetic neuralgia
    • diabetes mellitus
    • prolapsed intervertebral disc
  • amitriptyline, duloxetine, gabapentin or pregabalin are used as first line medication.
  • they are used as monotherapy. Not given as combinations.
  • Tolvaptan - Oral V2 antagonist -> causes free water loss
  • Conivaptan - IV antagonist of V2 and V1a.
  • (DDAVP = desmopressin)
  • Terlipressin etc.

[!INFO] Terlipressin is far better than vasopressin than for variceal bleeds.

  • Extradrenal tumours (paragangliomas) produce mainly noradrenaline. Others produce both. [[2020-BasicSciences-July#Autonomic nervous system and organization]]
    • Symptoms include the obvious ones as well as flushing / pallor, constipation or diarrhoea and Raynaud's phenomenon, polyuria and nocturia, glycosuria, orthostatic hypotension (possibly due to fluctuation of vascular tone).
    • Mnemonic: Phaeochromocytoma is associated with 1,2,3 :

  • Langerhans cells are antigen presenting cells but the abnormal cells in the disease have lower antigen presenting ability.
  • Birbeck granules present on EM: They have a "tennis racket" shape.
  • Is one cause of interstitial lung disease.
  • The disease involves the formation of multiple granulomas throughout the body.
    Adults commonly have single system involvement.
    • Only skin involvement -> Good prognosis; resection of local lesion can be curative.
    • Lung involvement -> bad prognosis
  • pituitary involvement -> commonest manifestation is diabetes insipidus.
  • Adults commonly have lytic lesions in the jaw and skull.
  • Upper and middle zone involvement is characteristic.
  • bone pain, typically in the skull or proximal femur
